Privacy policy

This project is open source, released under the GNU General Public
License version 3 or later (GPL-3.0-or-later).

XTE-DCDU consists of two components: an X-Plane 12 plugin and firmware
for an ESP32-S3 + LCD device. Neither component captures or uploads any
personally identifiable information.

Plugin (X-Plane)
----------------
- Reads the DCDU region of the ToLiss A320 panel texture from the
  simulator's GPU and forwards it, frame-by-frame, over a TCP socket
  on the user's local network to the address configured in
  `xte-dcdu.cfg`.
- Reads and writes only its own files inside the plugin directory:
  `xte-dcdu.cfg` (user configuration) and `xte-dcdu-dump.jpg` (only
  when the user explicitly triggers the `xtedcdu/dump_frame` command).
- Writes diagnostic messages (prefixed `XTE-DCDU:`) to X-Plane's
  local `Log.txt`. No log data leaves the user's machine.
- Makes no outbound connections to the internet. The only network
  traffic is the TCP session to the user-specified ESP32 address
  (or, in server mode, accepting an inbound connection from it) on
  the user's local network.

Firmware (ESP32-S3)
-------------------
- Connects to a Wi-Fi network using SSID and password supplied by the
  user in `firmware/credentials.ini`. These credentials are flashed
  into the device only and are never transmitted off-device.
- Receives DCDU frames over TCP from the plugin and displays them on
  the attached LCD. Sends button-press events back to the plugin over
  the same socket.
- Supports Arduino OTA on the local network for firmware updates
  initiated by the user.
- Makes no outbound connections to the internet, contains no
  telemetry, no analytics, and no remote logging.

No information about the user, the user's flights, or the user's
machine is visible to the developer or uploaded anywhere. The project
contains no ads, no tracking, no telemetry, and no third-party
services. It is truly free in both price and user freedom.

I hope you enjoy this free open source project for your X-Plane flight
simulator.

David Rowlandson

